<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09148c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09148c">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09148c"> 148(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> g to k, R</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A literal shibboleth killed all his kin in Egypt. The Mamelukes in Egypt rose and exterminated the Arabs of the Said, the <font color="green">[28]</font> passport to life being a mere consonant, not &ldquo;v&rdquo; then, but &ldquo;k,&rdquo; and the poor Arab died with a &ldquo;g&rdquo; in his mouth. Curiously and almost like the Luban, the choice of word was &ldquo;flour,&rdquo; and the Arab who said &ldquo;dagig&rdquo; instead of &ldquo;dakik&rdquo; died the &ldquo;G-death.&rdquo; <font color="green">[...]</font> In the Vemba language, therefore, &ldquo;f &rdquo; is the dominant note as against &ldquo;v.&rdquo; The same thing as what a Greek or Roman would do with a &ldquo;b&rdquo; or &ldquo;v&rdquo; in old High German, and which Grimm embodied in his law. The Vemba are Greeks and the Lubans are Germans. Again, <mark>&ldquo;g&rdquo; versus &ldquo;k&rdquo;</mark> is as much a joke as it was in Egypt, though not such a tragic one: curiously the tables are now turned, and the Rugarugas, who are the Arab ghillies or Mamelukes, cannot pronounce &ldquo;k,&rdquo; but boggle it into a &ldquo;g&rdquo;&mdash;exactly the opposite of the Said massacre. Another hint this of a sort of Grimm&apos;s law and in precisely the same relationship as that former: a German turned a Greek &ldquo;k&rdquo; into his Teutonic &ldquo;g.&rdquo; <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 27f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
